H0.text: Photosynthesis is the process during which cells use oxygen to release stored energy.

H1.text: Respiration is the process during which cells use oxygen to release stored energy.

H2.text: Circulation is the process during which cells use oxygen to release stored energy.

H3.text: Digestion is the process during which cells use oxygen to release stored energy.

A4.text: Cellular respiration is the process of oxidizing biological fuels using an inorganic electron acceptor, such as oxygen, to drive production of adenosine triphosphate (ATP), which stores chemical energy in a biologically accessible form.

A5.text: Plants are net consumers of carbon dioxide and producers of oxygen via photosynthesis, but plant respiration accounts for about half of the CO2 generated annually by terrestrial ecosystems.
